<div class="entry" id="entry-259980">
<h2 class="entry-header"><a rel="internal" href="http://fitnessblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2008/04/say-it-aint-so-dark-chocolate.html">Say it ain't so: Dark chocolate health benefits may not exist</a></h2>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top" width="55" style="padding-top: 2px;">

</td>
<td valign="top" style="padding-top: 2px;">
<div class="entryInfo"> <div class="authorName"><h4>By</h4> Lauren Lane Allison
<a rel="internal" href="/authors.html#Lauren Lane Allison"><br/></div>
<p>
<a href="mailto:llane&#64;dallasnews&#46;com">llane&#64;dallasnews&#46;com</a>
&nbsp;|&nbsp;
</p>
</div>
<div class="pubDate">
<p> 9:17 AM on Thu., Apr. 24, 2008 | <a rel="internal" class="permalink" href="http://fitnessblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2008/04/say-it-aint-so-dark-chocolate.html">Permalink</a></p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>

</table>
</div>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
     
    </div>
  <div id="blog-body">
    <div class="hot-entry">
      <p><span class="mt-enclosure mt-enclosure-image" style="display: inline;"><img alt="NH_Chocolate2.jpg" src="http://fitnessblog.dallasnews.com/NH_Chocolate2.jpg" width="200" height="288" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" /></span>Put down the candy bar.  It's back to the dark times when chocolate was unhealthy, no matter it's percentage of cocoa.</p>

<p>While browsing the <a href="http://peakperformance.runnersworld.com/2008/04/apr-13-whooops.html?cm_mmc=nutrition-_-2008_04_24-_-nutrition-_-NEWS%3a%20Dark%20Chocolate's%20Dark%20Side">Runner's World Blog</a> this morning, I came across the terrible news: a double-blind, placebo <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18400709">study by the Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University</a> found that dark chocolate may not have the health benefits we've been hearing about.  "This investigation failed to support the predicted beneficial effects of short-term dark chocolate and cocoa consumption on any of the neuropsychological or cardiovascular health-related variables included in this research."</p>

<p>Instead of producing the heart-healthy results all chocolate lovers were hoping for, the dark chocolate just managed to raise pulse rates.  And, of course, there's still the sugar, high fat, and calorie count to deal with.  </p>

<p>I guess chocolate will have to remain a treat after a long run instead of a dietary staple.  Darn.</p>
    </div>
